<HEADLINE>
<P>
PARENTS RECRUITING FOR PUBLIC EDUCATION; SCHOOLS: VALLEY COUPLE LEADS DRIVE 
AWAY FROM PRIVATE CAMPUSES. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By BETH SHUSTER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Down the hill from her Tarzana home, Kande Grabiner sees a gold mine. A small 
neighborhood school offering a full academic and enrichment program to students 
who don't need interviews or connections for admission. And it's free. 
</P>
<P>
 To Grabiner, all Wilbur Avenue Elementary needs is a few more committed 
parents like herself who are willing to give public schools a chance. In the 
past few months, Grabiner and her husband, Len, have turned their living room 
into a recruitment office, trying over coffee and dessert to persuade friends 
and neighbors to shun pricey private schools in favor of their neighborhood 
school down the street. 
</P>
<P>
 In launching their Wilbur School drive, the Grabiners join a group of parents 
and principals throughout the Los Angeles Unified School District and a growing 
effort by parent groups nationwide who are trying to recruit families back to 
public education with varying degrees of success. 
</P>
<P>
 "A lot of parents are fearful that their children won't get a quality 
education at the public school, but that's just not true," said Kande Grabiner. 
"I also had incorrect information. I thought my daughter would get a far better 
education in private school, but I don't believe that anymore." 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles educators are unable to put a number behind such recruitment 
efforts in the district. However, Deputy Supt. Dan Isaacs said, "Heck yes, this 
is happening all over the district, especially in schools where the leadership 
has a vision for (recruitment efforts) to occur." 
</P>
<P>
 Grabiner's efforts and others' mirror those of parent recruiters for public 
education throughout the country. A nonprofit organization called Parents for 
Public Schools began three years ago in Jackson, Miss., to combat the 
middle-class -- and mostly white -- flight from the public schools. The 
nonprofit group includes 35 chapters and about 10,000 members in a dozen 
states, including Arkansas, Texas and Colorado. There is not yet a chapter in 
California. 
</P>
<P>
 "Our mission is recruitment of middle-class parents, many of whom left (public 
schools) as a result of desegregation," said Kelly Butler, the group's interim 
executive director. "We are of the firm belief that public schools are the best 
place for our children to learn to live and work in a pluralistic society. Many 
people are sending their children to private and parochial schools without even 
considering the public school as an option." 
</P>
<P>
 Just six months ago, public schools weren't an option to the Grabiners, who 
worried about low test scores, crowded classes and how their child's education 
would be affected by the many Spanish-speaking students at the school. 
</P>
<P>
 But when Kande Grabiner heard other parents talking about competitive 
kindergarten interviews, applications and tuition at private schools, she 
realized they needed another option. "I felt like it was all about class and 
money -- who can afford the so-called best schools," Grabiner said. "It didn't 
feel right." 
</P>
<P>
 So she took a tour of Wilbur, a small campus of just 400 students, two fairly 
active parent groups, an after-school program and even a computer lab. Wilbur 
has 64% white students, 18% Latino students and 12% African American students. 
</P>
<P>
 The Grabiners find themselves in an uphill battle, however, trying to unravel 
a tangle of misperceptions and honest concerns about racial issues, class, 
poverty and crime that have prompted thousands of parents to leave public 
schools over the last two decades. Principals and parents in various parts of 
the sprawling district -- including Westchester, East and West Los Angeles and 
the west San Fernando Valley -- say they face similar problems. 
</P>
<P>
 The Grabiners have so far received a commitment from four other families. They 
are trying to work on about 10 more. 
</P>
<P>
 Geoff Abbott, a parent who attended a recent meeting at the Grabiners, was 
persuaded to enroll his son at Wilbur. "Meetings like this have opened our eyes 
to an alternative to spending $8,000 to $10,000 a year," Abbott said. "Maybe 
the public school system is getting an unfair shake. At age 5, I think you can 
take a chance." 
</P>
<P>
 But Jeff Domine is not so sure. Domine, who attended Los Angeles Unified 
schools and whose mother taught in the system for 30 years, said he is worried 
about crowded classrooms. 
</P>
<P>
 "Look, I personally would prefer public schools," Domine said. "My problem is 
with the numbers. Thirty kids to one teacher, I think, is a tough learning 
situation." 
</P>
<P>
 Ever since thousands of families fled the system during the busing era of the 
late 1970s, school officials say they have battled a tarnished public image. "I 
think there's a gap between what our schools are offering and what some parents 
believe we're offering," Isaacs said. 
</P>
<P>
 But while desegregation sparked "white flight" 20 years ago, parents now say 
their disinterest in public education stems more from their perceptions of the 
schools. They worry about overcrowded -- and hot -- classrooms, outdated 
textbooks, few enrichment courses and a bureaucratic school system that is 
removed from the teachers and students. 
</P>
<P>
 Los Angeles Unified faces all the problems of a large, urban school system, 
struggling to provide an education to a population of increasingly poor, 
immigrant children. Of the district's 636,400 students, 66% are Latino, 14.4% 
are African American and 12% are white. 
</P>
<P>
 Class sizes are among the highest in the nation, test scores typically dip 
below state and national averages and labor strife occurs almost annually. 
</P>
<P>
 For some parents, the school district doesn't offer the same nurturing 
environment they have seen in private schools. Nancy Kaczenski, a parent who 
attended the Grabiners' meeting, said she is turned off by the instability of 
the district. 
</P>
<P>
 "L.A. Unified is always on the brink of bankruptcy," said Kaczenski, who has 
not yet decided whether she will pull her child out of private school. "It has 
a terrible reputation." 
</P>
<P>
 Palisades High School Principal Merle Price, who recently held a special 
meeting with parents and their children who attend private schools, agrees that 
families lack confidence in the public school system. 
</P>
<P>
 But Price, who has opened the doors of his campus to private school parents 
and students, launched a successful recruitment drive this year, enrolling 100 
new students. 
</P>
<P>
 "When they see the climate of the school and the level of the educational 
program, that diffuses the rumors and misconceptions," Price said. 
</P>
<P>
 As a result of a new state law allowing parents to choose campuses, principals 
say they now are finding more private school families willing to consider 
public education. Under the open-enrollment policy, about 500 students 
districtwide left private schools for Los Angeles Unified campuses this year. 
</P>
<P>
 But often, when parents choose public schools, educators say they sometimes 
try to create a separate -- and unequal -- education for their children. Amy 
Stewart Wells, an assistant professor of education at UCLA, said some schools 
in more affluent areas are experiencing "second-generation desegregation" in 
which parents find ways to put their children into separate tracks -- honors 
classes, for example -- in which they create homogenous and segregated groups. 
</P>
<P>
 "We always talk about parent involvement as inherently good," Wells said. "But 
if they (parents) are resegregating schools, it could be educationally 
detrimental to the other children. 
</P>
<P>
 "I think if you buy into the concept of the neighborhood public school with 
diverse students and varying socioeconomic levels, you have to be aware of the 
kind of power you bring to it," Wells said. "I think parents need to look 
carefully at the whole school and the whole system." 
</P>
<P>
 That point is not lost on the Wilbur group, who all are parents of preschool 
children. At a recent meeting in the Grabiners' home, parents talked about 
paying for an aide in the kindergarten class to reduce class sizes. 
</P>
<P>
 "All of a sudden we change a kindergarten class; next year, we change a 
first-grade class and in three to four years, you have a metamorphosis," said 
Len Grabiner. 
</P>
<P>
 Wilbur Principal Richard Hickcox, who said he welcomes the Grabiners' 
recruitment efforts, said the entire school would benefit from more involved 
parents with time and money to donate. Hickcox said parents would be allowed to 
donate money for specific purposes, including an aide for one class.  
</P>
<P>
 "Parents hear bad things about the school district and then people apply that 
to their local neighborhood school and bad things really are not happening at 
the school," Hickcox said. "That's a problem of the reputation of the school 
district that, I think, we have to overcome." 
</P>
<P>
 Parent leaders at Wilbur say they applaud the Grabiners' efforts and believe 
any donations would be welcomed by the entire school. "You do it for all the 
kids," Karen Schreiber, the PTA co-president, told parents assembled in the 
Grabiners' living room the other night. "You're there, obviously, for your own 
child, but you are helping all the children. It's very worthwhile." 
</P>
</TEXT>
