<HEADLINE>
<P>
VALLEYWIDE FOCUS: GAY BUSINESS GROUP HOSTS AWARDS DINNER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAKI BECKER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Valley Business Alliance, a gay and lesbian organization, is hosting its 
16th annual president's dinner and awards presentation Jan. 14 at Sportsmen's 
Lodge in Studio City. 
</P>
<P>
 Alliance President Bill Robinson said the event is an opportunity for his 
organization to recognize people's contributions, regardless of sexual 
orientation, to the gay community and HIV/AIDS causes. 
</P>
<P>
 The recipient of the Humanitarian of the Year award is Miki Jackson, who has 
spent the past two years volunteering at Aunt Bee's Laundry Service, a 
Hollywood group that collects, washes and delivers the laundry of homebound 
victims of the AIDS virus, Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
 "The laundry service will be expanded to the Valley next year once they get 
another truck," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Also honored will be Bill Craig, owner and publisher of the gay and lesbian 
magazine Frontiers. 
</P>
<P>
 He also helps the LIFE AIDS lobbying group. 
</P>
<P>
 The media service award will go to Madam Dish Productions, which produces a 
gay talk and cooking show called "Dish" for public access television. 
</P>
<P>
 Started by Steven McCarthy, the show features McCarthy first interviewing a 
gay or lesbian guest -- anyone from Washington politicos to local playwrights 
-- at a couch in his home. 
</P>
<P>
 Then they cook a meal together in the kitchen and eat together, Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's a unique opportunity to communicate with the non-gay community and let 
them know about gay and lesbian people," Robinson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Tickets for the dinner cost $50 until Tuesday; $60 afterward. 
</P>
<P>
 For more information, call (818) 982-2650. MAKI BECKER 
</P>
</TEXT>
