<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUNG CAR BUFF, TRUCK DRIVER DIED IN PILEUP; TRAFFIC: WOMAN, 20, WAS GOING TO 
UPLAND WHEN HER CAR WAS HIT REPEATEDLY IN 30-CAR CRASH ON INTERSTATE 5. TRUCKER 
HAD WORKED FOR COMPANY FOR TWO YEARS. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARK SABBATINI, SPECIAL TO THE TIMES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Stacey Lynn Long loved cars -- including the Honda Civic she regularly drove 
from her father's home in Claremont to her boyfriend's apartment in 
Bakersfield. 
</P>
<P>
 In preparation for an upcoming local auto show, she was driving the car 
Wednesday to Upland to buy new tires when heavy fog suddenly fell on Interstate 
5 in the Tejon Pass, triggering a massive pileup involving at least 30 cars and 
more than a dozen big rigs. 
</P>
<P>
 Her car was hit repeatedly. Long, 20, was identified Thursday as one of two 
people who died in the massive wreck. 
</P>
<P>
 "She was very outgoing, had an excellent sense of humor and was a very caring, 
loving person," said Robert O'Connor, a friend of the family, speaking from the 
home of Long's mother in Helendale in San Bernardino County. 
</P>
<P>
 Long's interest in cars had been sparked by her boyfriend and her stepbrother. 
"It's something they've done all the way since high school," said her 
stepfather, Jim Falk. 
</P>
<P>
 The other person killed in the pileup was Miguel Angel Leanos, 34, of Chula 
Vista, whose trailer truck slammed into the back of a milk truck. The cab of 
Leanos' truck was so badly damaged that it took rescue workers several hours to 
free his body. 
</P>
<P>
 Leanos had worked for two years for J&J Trucking Co. of Chula Vista. "He was 
quiet," company owner Juan Fernandez said. "These things always seem to happen 
to the nicest people." 
</P>
<P>
 Leanos' wife and two children, who were riding in the cab, sustained only 
minor injuries in the crash, co-workers said. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities said Thursday that it could take several days to determine the 
exact cause of the deadly collisions that began after the fog cut visibility to 
almost zero about 12:30 p.m. Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Twenty-eight people reported being injured in the collision, although that 
number could increase, Officer Mark Ehly of the California Highway Patrol said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA123094-0105 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 112813 </DOCID>
