<HEADLINE>
<P>
DESCENDANT OF WALTER KNOTT REGAINS CONSCIOUSNESS; RECOVERY: DESIRE ANDERSON, 
17, THE GREAT-GRANDDAUGHTER OF THE PARK FOUNDER, WAS BLUDGEONED AT HER SAN 
DIEGO COUNTY HOME LAST MONTH. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By KEN ELLINGWOOD, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The great-granddaughter of the founder of Knott's Berry Farm has regained 
consciousness, a month after she was bludgeoned by an unknown attacker in her 
San Diego County home, officials said Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
 Desire Anderson, 17, of Fallbrook was moved to an undisclosed rehabilitation 
center in San Diego on Wednesday after regaining consciousness at Palomar 
Medical Center in Escondido, where she had been hospitalized since the Nov. 28 
attack.Her condition was upgraded to fair from serious, hospital officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 But investigators, who have not interviewed Anderson, said they do not expect 
her to lead them to the attacker. 
</P>
<P>
 "Even if she recovers 100%, it's not likely she'll remember anything," said 
homicide Lt. Doug Clements of the San Diego Sheriff's Department. 
</P>
<P>
 Investigators have said Anderson might have been asleep at the time of the 
attack, which occurred shortly after midnight. 
</P>
<P>
 Anderson's grandmother said Thursday that she was too shaken to discuss the 
girl's condition. 
</P>
<P>
 "She's really not lucid," said Marion Knott of Newport Beach. "I think being 
in rehab is a hopeful sign." 
</P>
<P>
 Family members had offered a $10,000 reward for information in the attack. 
</P>
<P>
 Clements said police have no leading suspects and have dismissed a number of 
tips. Among the suspects who didn't pan out was a parolee who lives in the same 
semirural neighborhood where Anderson lives on a four-acre ranch with her 
mother, Diane Anderson. Attempts to reach Diane Anderson were unsuccessful. 
</P>
<P>
 Desire Anderson, the great-granddaughter of park founder Walter Knott, is a 
senior and honor student at Fallbrook High School. Relatives said she excelled 
in French and was also training as a competitive figure skater. She had planned 
to apply to colleges this month in hopes of becoming a doctor someday, family 
members said. 
</P>
