<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING BRIEFING: IF BEST TON FOR TON MET BEST POUND FOR POUND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TIM KAWAKAMI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It will never happen, but Roy Jones Jr. can't help but wonder what it would be 
like to fight 46-year-old heavyweight champion George Foreman. 
</P>
<P>
 Jones, considered one of the world's top fighters, pound for pound, after 
dominating James Toney to win the International Boxing Federation 
super-middleweight title, says he could be very effective against Foreman. 
</P>
<P>
 "He would never land a punch," Jones says. "I would be the most frustrating 
opponent for him, because I would hit him eight or 10 times before he realized 
I had moved to a new position and would be whaling on him again. 
</P>
<P>
 "If I stood there with frozen feet in front of him, I wouldn't have time to be 
stupid, because I'd be in a coma." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Add Jones: "I can see why Foreman would want to fight Mike Tyson," Jones says. 
"First of all, he could make $30 million. But more importantly, he could win. 
</P>
<P>
 "Tyson would come straight at him like a bull, but George is crafty. He would 
be like the matador in those cartoons, holding the red cape with a big iron 
anvil hidden behind it." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia time: Don Shula is so closely identified with the Miami Dolphins' 
franchise, it's easy to forget he wasn't the team's first coach. Who was? 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 But has he been good? Bill Parcells, the workaholic coach of the New England 
Patriots, on whether he was looking for anything special under his Christmas 
tree: "I don't even know if I've got a tree." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Sugar-coated: Recently, Bert Sugar of Boxing Illustrated noticed that the 
Boston Globe ran a picture under a schedule of fights with a caption that read: 
"Joey Gamache gets a shot at the WBZ lightweight title Oct. 29." 
</P>
<P>
 "And you know what?" Sugar says, "They didn't get one letter telling them it 
was a typo and that Gamache would be fighting for the WB A title. 
</P>
<P>
 "Why do you think the typo went unnoticed? Because it's entirely possible, 
with sanctioning bodies multiplying like rabbits, that there really is a WBZ." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Fast start: Ross Atkin of the Christian Science Monitor points out the weird 
reality of the NFL's current expansion. 
</P>
<P>
 "Tom Coughlin, coach of the latest NFL team, the Jacksonville Jaguars, has a 
radio talk show," Atkin writes, "and his team doesn't even begin play until 
next year." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Trivia answer: George Wilson, who was 15-39-2 in the first four years of the 
franchise, before Shula took over in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Quotebook: New York Jet General Manager Dick Steinberg, on compiling a 32-49 
five-year record: "I've been around long enough to know what the record is. 
I've been in charge during that time. I can't stand on my record." TIM KAWAKAMI 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA123094-0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 112873 </DOCID>
