<HEADLINE>
<P>
CENTURY 21'S FALSE-ADVERTISING CLAIMS DISMISSED; COURTS: REAL ESTATE GIANT HAD 
COMPLAINED THAT SEVERAL OF RIVAL REMAX'S FRANCHISES DECEPTIVELY TOUTED BETTER 
SALES AND SERVICE. 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOHN O'DELL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A federal judge has dismissed real estate giant Century 21 International's 
allegations that several of competitor ReMax International Inc.'s local 
franchises made false advertising claims. 
</P>
<P>
 Century 21, based in Irvine, sued three ReMax franchises, including ReMax 
South County in Newport Beach, in early 1993 over an advertising campaign in 
which the offices maintained they were leaders in their markets. 
</P>
<P>
 But U.S. District Judge Alicemarie H. Stotler on Dec. 20 dismissed most of 
Century 21's complaints, saying they had no merit. 
</P>
<P>
 A Century 21 spokeswoman said Thursday that the company plans to appeal the 
ruling. She said the judge did not address Century 21's broader allegation that 
ReMax engages in false advertising when asserting that it has more sales and 
better customer service than other residential real estate brokers. 
</P>
<P>
 Meanwhile, ReMax, based in Denver, is suing Century 21 as part of the same 
case, alleging that it used inaccurate surveys to bolster its own claims of 
being No. 1. 
</P>
<P>
 Trial on that portion of the case is to begin in April in U.S. District Court 
in Santa Ana. 
</P>
<P>
 Major real estate chains such as Century 21 and ReMax are zealously protective 
of their performance claims because they see them as their main marketing tool 
in a residential market that has leveled off to about 3.8 million transactions 
a year.  
</P>
<P>
 With the aging of the baby-boom generation, which fueled that growth, the 
market is expected to begin shrinking shortly after the end of the decade -- a 
situation that has residential real estate brokers scrambling to remain 
competitive. 
</P>
<P>
 ReMax Chairman David Liniger said that Judge Stotler's Dec. 20 ruling, made 
public Thursday by ReMax, applies to Century 21's challenges to a number of 
ReMax TV commercials, an ad in an industry journal, statements about ReMax 
sales leadership printed in company newsletters and statements made by Liniger 
at his company's annual convention in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
 One of four ReMax TV spots challenged in the Century 21 lawsuit was not 
included in Stotler's summary judgment in favor of ReMax. Liniger said the 
company is filing a separate motion for dismissal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
