<HEADLINE>
<P>
WASTE FIRM TO PAY $325,000 TO SETTLE CONTRACT CLAIMS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON LEE, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Security Environmental Systems Inc. said Thursday it has agreed to pay 
$325,000 to settle various allegations of breach of contract and securities law 
violations. 
</P>
<P>
 But the waste-management company, based in Huntington Beach, said it still has 
some "significant" litigation issues to resolve. 
</P>
<P>
 The company also said it is now finalizing a tentative settlement with the 
California Department of Health Services involving state allegations that 
Security Environmental ran its Bakersfield operations without a proper permit. 
The state asked for damages and fines in excess of $8 million. 
</P>
<P>
 In the settlements announced Thursday, Security Environmental Systems said it 
would pay $325,000 to the various parties, $260,000 of it in installments 
beginning in June. 
</P>
<P>
 The money settles separate actions involving an alleged breach of contract to 
pay substantial commissions in 1992 and 1993 to third parties for waste 
contracts, an alleged breach of written contract to pay money in 1990 to an 
environmental consultant, and alleged violations of securities laws and 
breaches of contract involving a three-year warrant allegedly issued by the 
company in December, 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
