<P>
 grappa SIDE DISHES 
</P>
<P>
 It was a smashing year: The Northridge earthquake revised wine lists all over 
town. Most disheartening image: the river of wine flowing down Valentino's 
driveway. 
</P>
<P>
 New Age restaurant insurance (for harmonious success): Dial-a- Feng Shui.  
</P>
<P>
 Fastest about-face: Descanso changed from cutting-edge Caribbean to 
family-friendly eclectic. 
</P>
<P>
 Pilgrimage to Brentwood: Countless flock to Gratis for the fat-free 
triple-layer chocolate cake. BEST BARGAINS 
</P>
<P>
 Three-course ($12) lunch at Xiomara. 
</P>
<P>
 Salt cod & mashed potato brandade at Twin Palms ($3) -- cheaper than the valet 
parking. 
</P>
<P>
 Pasta with zucchini ($6.50) at Alto Palato. 
</P>
<P>
 $1 dinner salads (Cafe Bizou, Out Take Cafe). 
</P>
<P>
 50-cent egg cream at Barney Greengrass. 
</P>
<P>
 $2.50 gingerbread at Basix. THE FINE PRINT 
</P>
<P>
 Copywriter wanted: "To share a more passionate and satisfying experience with 
a group of friends, you'd pretty much have to get naked" (ad for Dominick's 
East Village "Italian food to die for"). 
</P>
<P>
 Awwwwwwwwwww: Pasta at Provencia is "created with love every day." 
</P>
<P>
 Talk's cheap: "Gratis: fat-free cuisine. Because you wouldn't know if we 
didn't say it. That's right, delicious food that just happens to be fat free." 
</P>
<P>
 That's life: "On our cover letter we stated that Vida means life in Japanese. 
In fact it means life in Spanish." (from a press release) 
</P>
<P>
 Is that a noun or a verb?: "Creeque Alley, Bar & Ball" (from Creeque Alley's 
menu). A LA CARTE 
</P>
<P>
 Not-yet-famous chefs club: Vida's Fred Eric and his chef pals meet to plot the 
overthrow of Puck, Splichal, et al. 
</P>
<P>
 The captive cook: Don't expect to eat Ken Frank's food at the House of Blues' 
exclusive Foundation Room unless you can cough up the hefty membership fee. Or 
have friends in high places. 
</P>
<P>
 Escrow eternal: A Westside Yujean Kang? 
</P>
<P>
 Don't ask questions you don't want to hear the answer to: Waiters who gush, 
"Is everything fabulous?" AND THE SAGA CONTINUES 
</P>
<P>
 And the new host is . . . Spago closed last Oscar night to honor Swifty Lazar. 
Where will the A-list party in 1995? 
</P>
<P>
 Haven't they paid their light bill yet?: The waiters at Chianti still whip out 
flashlights so customers can read the menu. 
</P>
<P>
 Problems with intimacy?: Restaurants too noisy for talk: Il Fornaio 
(Pasadena), Gordon Biersch, Creeque Alley, Chinois, Typhoon.  
</P>
<P>
 Why are these people still waiting?: Mi Piace. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 -- Compiled by Kathie Jenkins, S. Irene Virbila and Michelle Huneven 
